{{nihongo title|Shadow of the Colossus|ワンダと巨像|Wanda to Kyozō|lit. "''Wander and the colossus''"}} is a [[Japan]]ese-developed [[action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Sony Computer Entertainment]] (SCEI) for the [[PlayStation 2]]. The game was released in [[North America]] and Japan in October [[2005 in video gaming|2005]] and [[PAL region|PAL territories]] in February [[2006 in video gaming|2006]].<ref name="release info">{{cite web | editor=IGN site staff | year=2006 | title=IGN: Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://ps2.ign.com/objects/490/490849.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=July 29 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> The game was created by SCEI's International Production Studio 1, the same development team responsible for the cult hit<ref name="cult-eurogamer">{{cite web | author=Reed, Kristan | title=The Bluffer's Guide To PS2 Cult Classics | url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=56384 | work=[http://eurogamer.net Eurogamer.net| accessdate=12 April|accessyear=2007}}</ref> ''[[Ico]]''.<ref name="psau">{{cite web | author=PlayStation.com Australia site staff | title=NICO: the game that never was | url=http://au.playstation.com/news/sotc_nico.jhtml | work=[http://au.playstation.com/ PlayStation.com Australia] | accessdate=July 30|accessyear=2006}}</ref>

The game focuses on a young man named Wander who must travel across a vast expanse on horseback and defeat sixteen [[giant (mythology)|giants]], beings collectively known as colossi, to restore the life of a girl. The game is unusual within the action-adventure genre in that there are no towns or [[dungeon (games)|dungeons]] to explore, no characters with which to interact, and no enemies to defeat, other than the colossi.<ref name="colossalcreation">{{cite web | author=McNamara, Andy & Berghammer, Billy | year=2006 | title=Colossal Creation: The Kenji Kaido and Fumito Ueda Interview | url=http://www.gameinformer.com/News/Story/200602/N06.0216.1853.30213.htm | work=[http://www.gameinformer.com/ Game Informer] | accessdate=July 9 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="behindtheshadow">{{cite web | author=Kohler, Chris | year=2006 | title=Behind the Shadow: Fumito Ueda | url=http://www.wired.com/news/technology/0,70286-0.html | work=[http://www.wired.com/ Wired News] | accessdate=July 9|accessyear=2006}}</ref> ''Shadow of the Colossus'' has been described as a [[computer puzzle game|puzzle]] game, as each colossus' weakness must be identified and exploited before it can be defeated.<ref name="gamespotreview">{{cite web | author=Shoemaker, Brad | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus for PlayStation 2 Review | url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/adventure/wandaandthecolossus/review.html | work=[http://www.gamespot.com/ GameSpot] | accessdate=July 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="eurogamer">{{cite web | author=Reed, Kristan | year=2005 | title=Review – Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=61436 | work=[http://www.eurogamer.net/ Euro Gamer] | accessdate=July 21 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

==Gameplay==

===Basics===
Progression through ''Shadow of the Colossus'' occurs in cycles. Beginning at a central point in an expansive landscape, the player seeks out and defeats a colossus, and is then returned to the central point to repeat the process.<ref name="gamespotreview" /> To find each colossus, Wander must raise his [[sword]] while in a sunlit area to reflect beams of light, which will converge when the sword is pointed in the right direction of the next encounter.<ref name="ignpreview2">{{cite web | author=Dunham, Jeremy | year=2005 | title=Pre-E3 2005: Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/608/608001p1.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=August 16 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> The journey to a colossus is seldom a straightforward matter—stretches of varied terrain often require that a detour be taken along the way. Most colossi are located in remote areas, such as atop cliffs or within ancient structures, and tend to be located progressively farther away from the central area.

Once a colossus is found, the player must discover its weaknesses to defeat it. Each colossus dwells in a unique lair, and many colossi cannot be defeated without making use of the surrounding environment.<ref name="ignpreview3">{{cite web | author=Sulic, Ivan | year=2005 | title=A Colossus Falls | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/641/641470p1.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=August 16 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> Every colossus has at least one weak point, indicated by a glowing [[sigil (magic)|sigil]].<ref name="giantleap">{{cite web | author=Kohler, Chris | year=2005 | title=Colossus Is Giant Leap for Games | url=http://www.wired.com/news/games/0,2101,69334,00.html | work=[http://www.wired.com/ Wired News] | accessdate=July 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> If the area is lit by sunlight, the player may use the sword's reflected light to temporarily illuminate these sigils.<ref name="ignpreview2" /><ref name="ignpreview4">{{cite web | author=Dunham, Jeremy | year=2005 | title=E3 2005: Shadow of the Colossus Update | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/616/616095p1.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=August 16|accessyear=2006}}</ref> Each colossus has areas covered with [[fur]] or protruding ledges, which the player may use to grip and scale the colossus while it thrashes about in an attempt to dislodge the player.<ref name="gamespotreview" /> While scaling a colossus, the player must act quickly, as Wander has a limited grip gauge that decreases while he hangs onto the creature.

[[Image:SotCglyphstab.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Wander stabbing the sigil on Valus, the first colossus]]
Wander and the colossi have [[Health (game mechanism)|life bars]] to indicate their remaining health. The colossi's health will decrease significantly when their weak points are attacked, while Wander can be harmed by a colossus' attacks or falls from great heights. Throughout the game, Wander is equipped with only a sword and a [[bow (weapon)|bow]]<ref name="giantleap" /> , although different items can be obtained by completing Time Attack mode.

===Agro and the environment===
Wander's horse, Agro, plays a large role in the game. In addition to serving as a means of transportation, Agro is vital in defeating some of the Colossi.<ref name="ignpreview">{{cite web | author=Gantayat, Anoop | year=2005 | title=Wanda and the Colossus | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/546/546753p1.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=August 16 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> There are, however, many places that Agro cannot reach. Colossi often inhabit areas beyond deep water or obstacles that must be scaled. Agro cannot travel beyond these, and when separated from Wander by such obstacles, cannot participate in the following battle.<ref name="ignpreview2" />

The environment must be used to the player's advantage more often as the game progresses. The first two battles take place on simple, large, flat areas of land, with the only goal being to discover how to scale the colossi and attack their weak points.<ref name="ignpreview2" /><ref name="ignpreview3" /> However, the majority of the following fourteen battles require that some aspect of the battlefield be used.<ref name="eurogamer" /><ref name="ignreview">{{cite web | author=Roper, Chris | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus Review | url=http://ps2.ign.com/articles/658/658991p2.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=July 21 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

==Plot and setting==
During ''Shadow of the Colossus'', the player receives little information concerning the backstories of the characters and their relationships with one another.<ref name="gamespotreview" /> The game clearly takes place in a [[fantasy]] setting,<ref name="gamespyreview">{{cite web | author=McGarvey, Sterling | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus Review | url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/ico-ii/658966p1.html | work=[http://gamespy.com/ GameSpy] | accessdate=17 August | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="fantasysetting">{{cite web | author=Daultrey, Stephen | year=2004 | title=An epic called Wanda: Sony's "awesome" PS2 works uncovered | url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=109139 | work=[http://www.computerandvideogames.com/ computerandvideogames]|accessdate=August 17| accessyear=2006}}</ref> with most of the game's events occurring within a vast and unpopulated [[peninsula]] separated from the outside world by a mountain range to its North and sea to the South and East. The presence of ruins and other ancient structures indicate that the area was once a settlement.<ref name="ignreview" /><ref name="ruins">{{cite web | author=Scott, Alan Marriott | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus Preview | url=http://www.g4tv.com/xplay/features/52381/Shadow_of_the_Colossus_Preview.html | work=[http://www.g4tv.com/ G4] | accessdate=August 16 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="newyorkmagazine">{{cite web | author=Hayes, Jonahthan | year=2005 | title=Larger than Life – New York Magazine Video Game Review | url=http://newyorkmetro.com/nymetro/arts/games/reviews/15173/ | work=[http://newyorkmetro.com/ New York Arts & Events] | accessdate=July 28 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="ruins2">{{cite web | author=Andrews, Stuar | year=2006 | title=Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.trustedreviews.com/article.aspx?page=5814&head=0 | work=[http://www.trustedreviews.com/index.aspx TrustedReviews] | accessdate=August 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

The region is only accessible via a small cleft in the mountains to the north, leading to a massive stone bridge. This bridge spans half the distance of the landscape and terminates at a large temple called the "Shrine of Worship" located at its center. It is, however, forbidden to enter the land,<ref name="dorminandshrine">'''Emon (narrating):''' That place… began from the resonance of intersecting points… They are memories replaced by ens and naught and etched into stone. Blood, young sprouts, sky—and the one with the ability to control beings created from light… In that world, it is said that if one should wish it one can bring back the souls of the dead… …But to trespass upon that land is strictly forbidden… {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> which is characterized by diverse geographical features, such as [[lake]]s and [[desert]]s, in addition to man-made structures.<ref name="gamespotreview" /><ref name="ignreview" />

===Characters===
[[Image:Mono and Wander.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Wander standing before Mono]]
The [[protagonist]] of the game is Wander (voiced by [[Kenji Nojima]]), a young man whose goal is to [[resurrection|resurrect]] a girl named "Mono" (voiced by [[Hitomi Nabatame]]). Little is known about Mono other than that she was somehow [[human sacrifice|sacrificed]] because she was believed to have a cursed destiny.<ref>'''Wander:''' She was sacrificed for she has a cursed fate.  Please, I need you to bring back her soul… {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> Assisting Wander in his quest to revive her is his loyal horse, Agro, who serves as his only ally in defeating the colossi.<ref name="official site">{{cite web | author=Sony Computer Entertainment staff | year=2006 | title=Shadow of the Colossus English (UK) | url=http://www.shadowofthecolossus.com/ | work=[http://www.shadowofthecolossus.com/ Shadow of the Colossus official site] | accessdate=July 29|accessyear=2006}}</ref> The story revolves around these three characters, but features a small supporting cast including Dormin (voiced by [[Kazuhiro Nakata]] and [[Kyoko Hikami]]) and Lord Emon (voiced by [[Naoki Bando]]).

Referring to itself in the [[plural]] and speaking with two voices at once (one male and one female), Dormin is a mysterious, disembodied entity consisting of several beings that reside in the Shrine of Worship.<ref name="official site" /> Its physical form was severed into sixteen components many years before the beginning of the game, and became sealed within the colossi for unexplained reasons.<ref name="dorminsealed">'''Dormin:''' Thou severed Our body into sixteen segments for an eternity in order to seal away Our power… {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> In [[legend]]s of the game's world, it is said that Dormin has the power to revive the dead,<ref name="dorminandshrine" /><ref name="official site" /> and it is for this reason that Wander enters the forbidden land, seeking its assistance in reviving Mono. Dormin offers to revive her in exchange for Wander destroying the sixteen colossi.<ref name="dorminrequest">'''Wander:''' Please, I need you to bring back her soul… / '''Dormin:''' That maiden's soul? Souls that are once lost cannot be reclaimed… Is that not the law of mortals? With that sword, however… it may not be impossible. / '''Wander:''' Really?! / '''Dormin:''' That is of course, if thou manage to accomplish what We askest. / '''Wander:''' What do I have to do? / '''Dormin:''' Behold the idols that stand along the wall… Thou art to destroy all of them. But those idols cannot be destroyed by the mere hands of a mortal… / '''Wander:''' Then what am I to do? / '''Dormin:''' In this land there exist colossi that are the incarnations of those idols. If thou defeat those colossi—the idols shall fall. {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref>

Lord Emon is a [[shamanism|shaman]] who narrates a vision in the game's introduction, vaguely explaining the origin of the land Wander has come to, and emphasising that entry to this place is forbidden.<ref name="dorminandshrine" /> He is portrayed as having extensive knowledge regarding the containment of Dormin, and the ability to use powerful [[magic (paranormal)|magic]]. He has a small group of soldiers at his command, and is pursuing Wander to prevent the use of "the forbidden spell", the ritual involving the destruction of the sixteen colossi.<ref>'''Emon:''' Have you any idea what you've done?! Not only did you steal the sword and trespass upon this cursed land, you used the forbidden spell as well… {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref>

The colossi are armored, most often enormous creatures with forms ranging from various humanoids to predatory animals. Their bodies are a fusion of rock, earth, fur, and architectural elements (some parts weathered or fractured). When trespassing upon their territory, the player is ignored by some colossi, while others will attack on sight.<ref name="gamespotreview" /><ref name="pressstart">{{cite web | author=Schilling, Chris | year=2006 | title=Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.pressstartonline.co.uk/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=125&Itemid=43 | work=[http://www.pressstartonline.co.uk/ Press Start Online] | accessdate=August 8 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> Inhabiting specific locations in the forbidden land, they do not venture outside their own territory. Once slain they will remain where fallen as a mound of earth and rock vaguely resembling the original colossus.<ref name="crumble">{{cite web | author=Gillett, Nick | year=2006 | title=Preview Guitar Hero | Shadow Of The Colossus | url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguide/games/story/0,,1705970,00.html | work=[http://www.guardian.co.uk/ Guardian Unlimited] | accessdate=August 8 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="crumble2">{{cite web | author=IGN site staff | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus Cheats, Code and Cheat Codes | url=http://cheats.ign.com/ob2/068/490/490849.html | work=[http://ign.com/ IGN] | accessdate=August 8 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

[[Image:SotCno13.JPG|left|thumb|200px|Wander and Agro pursuing the thirteenth colossus, Phalanx, a flying serpent]]

===Story===
<!--

STOP! If the first thing that went through your mind when you saw the word "Story" was to add a spoiler tag, then you have proved to yourself that other people will also realize that "Story" is synonymous with "spoiler" and thus a spoiler tag is unnecessary.

-->
The story of ''Shadow of the Colossus'' begins as Wander enters the forbidden land, traveling across the long bridge at its entrance on his horse, Agro. Led to the massive Shrine of Worship at the center of the region, Wander carries with him a body wrapped in a cloak, which he lays upon an altar in the shrine. Removing the cloak, the body of a maiden named "Mono" is revealed. A moment later, several shadow-like creatures with humanoid forms appear and prepare to attack Wander, but he easily dismisses them with a wave of an ancient sword in his possession. After vanquishing the shadow creatures, the voice of the disembodied entity known as "Dormin" echoes from above, expressing surprise that Wander possesses the weapon. Wander requests that Dormin return Mono's soul to her body, which they state may be possible, but only if the sixteen [[cult image|idol]]s lining the temple's hall are destroyed. They explain that this task can only be accomplished by using the ancient sword to kill sixteen colossi located throughout the land. Each contains a portion of Dormin's own essence, though this is not revealed until late in the game.<ref name="dorminsealed" /><ref name="dorminrequest" />

Despite a warning from Dormin that he may have to pay a great price to revive Mono,<ref>'''Dormin:''' But heed this, the price you pay may be heavy indeed. / '''Wander:''' It doesn't matter. {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> Wander sets out to search the land for the colossi and destroy them. With the death of each colossus, his physical appearance deteriorates, his skin becoming paler and his hair darker. Meanwhile, Mono's complexion improves and her voice can be faintly heard after each colossus has been killed. After the death of the twelfth, it is revealed to the player that Wander is being pursued by a group of warriors led by the shaman called "Lord Emon". 

Urged to hurry with his task by Dormin, Wander soon heads off to defeat the sixteenth and final colossus. On the way to this confrontation, he travels on horseback across a long bridge, which begins to collapse as he is halfway across.  As Agro jumps over the last gap in the bridge, the portion he lands on begins to separate from its foundation, causing Agro to nearly lose his footing. Sensing the impending fall, Agro jerks forward to throw Wander to safety on the other side, sacrificing himself as the bridge finally gives way and he falls into the river hundreds of feet below. Lord Emon's company arrives in the Shrine of Worship just as the last temple idol crumbles, and Wander appears soon after, his eyes and skin now both entirely pale, and two small horns protruding from his head. Declaring that Wander has been possessed, Lord Emon orders his warriors to kill him.<ref>'''Emon:''' Eradicate the source of the evil. Look… He's possessed by the dead. Hurry up and do it! It is better to put him out of his misery than to exist, cursed as he is. {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> While he struggles to reach Mono, one warrior shoots Wander in the leg with a [[crossbow]], while another stabs him through his heart with a sword. Black blood sprays from the wound as Wander's body becomes covered in darkness and falls to the floor—a death identical to those suffered by the colossi.

Afterward, Dormin's spirit possesses Wander's body, transforming it into a shadowy giant. They explain that their own body was separated to seal away their power.<ref name="dorminsealed"> and that they have now borrowed Wander's, each freed component of Dormin's essence having been stored inside.<ref>'''Dormin:''' We have borrowed the body of this warrior... {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref> While his men flee, Lord Emon casts the ancient sword used to kill the colossi into a small pool at the back of the temple's hall, creating a whirlwind of light that consumes both Dormin and Wander. Emon and his men flee the forbidden land as the bridge connecting to the temple collapses behind them. As they safely arrive at the entrance to the forbidden land, Emon expresses hope that if Wander survived, he will someday be able to atone for his actions.<ref>'''Emon:''' Poor ungodly soul… Now, no man shall ever trespass upon this place again. Should you be alive… If it's even possible to continue to exist in these sealed lands…one day, perhaps you will make atonement for what you've done. {{cite video game|title=Shadow of the Colossus |developer=Sony Computer Entertainment |publisher=Sony Computer Entertainment |date=2005-10-18 |platform=PlayStation 2 |language=English}}</ref>

In the temple, Mono awakens, restored by Dormin in accordance with their agreement with Wander, and Agro limps into the temple with a broken (or possibly heavily sprained) hind leg. Mono follows him to the pool into which Wander and Dormin were pulled by Emon's spell, finding a male [[infant]] with tiny [[horn (anatomy)|horns]] on his head. She takes the child with her, following the horse to higher levels of the Shrine of Worship, and arrives at a secret garden within the shrine as the game ends.

===Connections to ''Ico''===
''Shadow of the Colossus'' is considered both a [[spiritual successor]]<ref name="pressrelease">{{cite web | editor=GameSpot site staff | year=2005 | title=The Long-Awaited Spiritual Successor to ICO Arrives Mid-February in Europe | editor=GameSpot site staff | url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/adventure/wandaandthecolossus/news.html?sid=6141938 | work=[http://www.gamespot.com/ GameSpot] | accessdate=July 1|accessyear=2006}}</ref> and prequel to ''[[Ico]]''.<ref name="colossalcreation" /> For several months during and after the game's release, the game's director and lead designer, [[Fumito Ueda]], maintained that the game's status as a prequel was simply his personal take on the game and not necessarily its [[canon (fiction)|canon]] nature, as he largely intended for players to decide the specifics of the story for themselves. However, during an interview in March 2006, Ueda revealed that a specific connection between the two games exists: the world featured in the two is the same, with ''Shadow of the Colossus'' taking place at an unspecified time before ''Ico''. He revealed that Wander sires the line of horned boys of which ''Ico''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s protagonist is a descendant.<ref name="behindtheshadow" /> Moreover, the shadowy figures which appear in the Shrine of Worship are connected to the shadows which the player must fight in ''Ico''.<ref name="official site" /> Both games use unique [[artistic language|fictional languages]] as well.<ref name="languages">{{cite web | author=The Gaming Intelligence Agency site staff | year=2001 | title=Interview with Fumito Ueda | url=http://terror.snm.zhdk.ch/mirrors/thegia/sites/www.thegia.com/features/f010831.html | work=[http://www.thegia.com/ The Gaming Intelligence Agency] | accessdate=August 2 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="languages2">{{cite web | author=Bettenhausen, Shane | year=2005 | title=Afterthoughts: Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3145476 | work=[http://www.1up.com/ 1UP.com] | accessdate=August 2 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

==Development==
[[Image:SotCNicoshot.JPG|thumb|200px|right|A screenshot from ''Nico'', depicting battle with an early colossus design]]
With a team of thirty-five people, ''Shadow of the Colossus'' began development in [[2002 in video gaming|2002]] under the project name "''Nico''" and was intended to be a direct sequel to ''Ico''.<ref name="psau" /><ref name="makingcolossalgames">{{cite web | author=Kosak, Dave "Fargo" | year=2006 | title=Making Colossal Games | url=http://ps2.gamespy.com/playstation-2/ico-ii/688379p2.html | work=[http://ps2.gamespy.com/ GameSpy] | accessdate=July 18 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> The name "''Nico''" itself is a [[portmanteau]] of the [[Japanese language|Japanese]] word ''ni'' (二; "two") and "''Ico''".<ref name="psau" /> An early [[technology demo]] for the project shown at the DICE Summit in [[2003 in video gaming|2003]] depicted a group of masked, horned boys riding horses while attacking and defeating a colossus.<ref name="psau" /><ref name="makingcolossalgames" /> However, Fumito Ueda expressed that, at the time, it was simpler to reuse the character design of ''Ico''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s protagonist, and that he never explicitly desired a sequel to ''Ico''.<ref name="psnz">{{cite web | editor=PlayStation.com New Zealand site staff | title=A Colossus Speaks | url=http://www.nz.playstation.com/news/shadow_of_the_colossus_qna.jhtml;jsessionid=PKA23GLV1NC5XS3YIXZCFE4LXBC5GIV0 | work=[http://www.nz.playstation.com/ PlayStation.com New Zealand] | accessdate=July 30|accessyear=2006}}</ref> Japanese [[pre-order]]s of ''Shadow of the Colossus'' later included a bonus [[DVD]] with the concept video, a trailer describing ''Nico''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s plot, and an introduction the development team states they wanted to use in ''Shadow of the Colossus''.

Ueda and producer Kenji Kaido held their team to a high standard throughout production. An admitted perfectionist, Ueda felt that only one or two out of 500 artists who applied to work on ''Shadow of the Colossus'' met his criteria, and often demanded thorough changes in design until it matched his vision.<ref name="makingcolossalgames" /> For his part, Kaido challenged the programmers to meet the concept of realistic physics in relation to the movement of the colossi and the subsequent effect this movement would have for Wander, both in terms of how he might be displaced and how he may be able to use this movement to his advantage. For instance, if a colossus were to shake, Kaido wanted Wander's position to shift realistically in response. Additionally, if a colossus' limb was currently horizontal, Kaido wanted the player to be able to run across the limb as though it were any other flat surface. He referred to these two concepts as "player dynamics and reactions" and "organic collision deformation".<ref name="makingcolossalgames" /> The realistic physics engine produced as a result required that faster colossi had to be smaller as well.<ref name="psnz" />

[[Image:Kaido Kenji And Fumito Ueda.jpg‎|thumb|200px|[[Kenji Kaido]](left), producer of the game, and [[Fumito Ueda]], lead designer of the game at Art Futura 2005]]
Ueda wished the game to have a unique presentation<ref name="colossalcreation" /> and change how both players and developers perceived the idea of what [[boss (video games)|bosses]] should be in video games. To achieve this, he ensured that the game's only enemies would be the sixteen colossi, that they could only be approached one at a time, and that they would have various behavior patterns.<ref name="psnz" /><ref name="1up">{{cite web | author=Mielke, James | year=2005 | title=Shadow Talk: Interview with Fumito Ueda and Kenji Kaido | url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?cId=3144673 | work=[http://www.1up.com/ 1UP.com] | accessdate=July 23|accessyear=2006}}</ref> Though limiting the presence of enemies to only bosses was partly intended to differentiate the game from others, Ueda also expressed that it was to ensure that the programmers' focus was entirely on the colossi so that their quality would be as high as possible.<ref name="behindtheshadow" /> In accordance with this focus upon the colossi—and his preference for simple controls—he intended that one button on the [[game controller]] be used solely for targeting the colossi during battles.<ref name="1up" />

A theme of companionship between the player and an [[game artificial intelligence|AI]]-controlled partner was a concern for Ueda.<ref name="1up" /> In ''Ico'', this theme was presented through the protagonist and the character Yorda, whom the player was required to work with and protect while navigating the game's environments.<ref name="1up2">{{cite web | author=Mielke, James & Rybicki, Joe | year=2005 | title=A Giant In The Making | url=http://www.1up.com/do/feature?pager.offset=2&cId=3143702 | work=[http://www.1up.com/ 1UP.com] | accessdate=July 30 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> As such, another key element in ''Shadow of the Colossus'' is the relationship between Wander and his horse, Agro.<ref name="ignpreview" /> Intended to be a realistic representation of a horse, Agro does not always respond to commands. In Ueda's words, "a real horse … doesn't always obey. It's not like a car or a motorcycle, it won't always turn when you say 'turn!'" However, he has admitted that the team had to seek a balance in how often Agro didn't respond to commands so as to not sacrifice playability in the pursuit of realism.<ref name="1up" />

All elements of the game—including audio, gameplay and visuals—were used to achieve an atmosphere of a "lonely hero", which Ueda considered important in the development of the game. Lighting, in particular, was used to establish a dark, fearsome setting for the forbidden land, while the protagonist's sword would provide a means of navigation that was "direct and only expressible visually".<ref name="1up2" />

Like ''Ico'', ''Shadow'' uses a distinct style of lighting. The game's [[game engine|engine]] uses elements such as [[saturation (color theory)|desaturated colors]], [[motion blur]] and partial [[high dynamic range rendering]], with a heavy emphasis on [[bloom (shader effect)|bloom lighting]].<ref name="eurogamer" /><ref name="makingofsotc">{{cite web | author=Nishikawa | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus PS2 Preview | url=http://www.watch.impress.co.jp/game/docs/20051207/3dwa.htm | work=[http://www.watch.impress.co.jp Impress Watch] | accessdate=2 August | accessyear=2006}} Translation available at [http://www.dyingduck.com/sotc/making_of_sotc.html The Making of "Shadow of the Colossus"]</ref><ref name="ignpreview">{{cite web | author=IGN site staff | year=2005 | title=Shadow of the Colossus PS2 Preview | url=http://www.1up.com/do/previewPage?cId=3142480&did=1 | work=[http://www.1up.com/ 1UP.com] | accessdate=August 2 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

==Audio==
{{main|Shadow of the Colossus: Roar of the Earth}}
[[Image:Roar of the Earth - Cover.jpg|thumb|175px|''Roar of the Earth'' soundtrack cover]]
While the game has an extensive orchestral soundtrack, the music is only heard during [[cut scene]]s and colossi encounters, while time spent at the Shrine of Worship and traversing the landscape is silent save for the sounds made by the protagonist, his horse and their surroundings.<ref name="shadowreview">{{cite web | author=Ramsey | year=2006 | title=Review of Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.gamechew.com/review.php?id=2| work=[http://www.gamechew.com GameChew] | accessdate=July 29 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> The open nature of the game world and lack of life, coupled with this limited use of music, aids in establishing an atmosphere of solitude,<ref name="1up2" /><ref name="instantreview">{{cite web | author=Rogers, Tim | year=2005 | title=Review of Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.insertcredit.com/reviews/wanda/ | work=[http://www.insertcredit.com insert credit] | accessdate=July 29 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> similar to that of Ico.<ref name="ignreview" />

''[[Shadow of the Colossus: Roar of the Earth|Roar of the Earth]]'' is the [[soundtrack]] to ''Shadow of the Colossus''. It was released in Japan on [[December 7]], [[2005 in music|2005]]. There are currently no announced plans to release the album in other territories. The game's score was composed by [[Kō Ōtani]] (credited in-game as "Kow Otani"), whose previous video game work included the soundtracks to the PlayStation 2 flight simulator ''[[Sky Odyssey]]'' and the [[PlayStation]] shooter ''[[Philosoma]]''. He has also worked on several of the 1990s-era [[Gamera]] films, as well as a variety of [[anime]]. ''Roar of the Earth'' won the award for "Soundtrack of the Year" in the [[United States|US]]-based [[video game magazine]] ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]''.<ref name="egmsoty">{{cite web | date=November, 2005 | url=http://www.findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_zdegm/is_200511/ai_n15614448/pg_2 | title=Shadow of the Colossus Electronic Gaming Monthly | work=[http://www.findarticles.com/ Find Articles] | accessdate=July 30 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

==PAL version==
The [[PAL region|PAL]] version of the game was released in February 2006. Much like the PAL release for ''Ico'', the game came in cardboard packaging displaying various pieces of artwork from the game, and contained four art cards.<ref name="extrasandico">{{cite web | editor=Wales, Matt | year=2006 | title=PAL Colossus gets exclusive content | url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=133500 | work=[http://www.computerandvideogames.com/ computerandvideogames] | accessdate=July 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="extrasandico2">{{cite web | editor=Unlikely Hero Limited | year=2006 | title=PlayStation 2 News | url=http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/7f/news/mustn-t-repeat-dismal-failure-of-ico-launch--mustn-t-repeat-dismal-failure-of-ico-launch-3a377f.html | work=[http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/ Yahoo! Games UK & Ireland] | accessdate=July 30 | accessyear=2006}} Original link found to be inactive on 16 August 2006.</ref><ref name="artcards">{{cite web | editor=Li, Felix M.C. a.k.a. "Maskrider" | year=2006 | title=Zone of the Gamers: Wanda to Kyozou/Shadow of the Colossus Scans/Photos | url=http://z-o-g.org/gallery2/ico/watc/ | work=[http://z-o-g.org/ Zone Of the Gamers] | accessdate=July 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

The game also came with a "making of" documentary, a trailer for ''Ico'' and a gallery of [[concept art]], accessible from the game's main menu.<ref name="extrasandico" /> Sony Computer Entertainment also re-released ''Ico'' in PAL territories at the time of ''Shadow''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s release, both to promote the game through ''Ico''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s reputation, and to allow players who did not buy ''Ico'' during its original limited release to complete their collections.<ref name="extrasandico" /><ref name="extrasandico2" /><ref name="icorerelease">{{cite web | editor=Wales, Matt | year=2006 | title=Fumito Ueda | url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/article.php?id=132780 | work=[http://www.computerandvideogames.com/ computerandvideogames] | accessdate=July 17 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

Some confusion has arisen in PAL regions concerning the official name of the protagonist, due primarily to the manual's usage of "Wanda", while the North American manual and the game itself uses the name "Wander". The name ワンダ (''Wanda''), as written in this title, is in fact the common transliteration of the English name "Wanda".  The English word "wonder" is written as ワンダー (''wandaa''), with a long ''a''.  The long ''a'' is the standard transliteration for the English -er ending.

==Reception==
''Shadow of the Colossus''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s commercial reception was positive, with sales of 140,000 copies in its first week at retail in Japan, reaching number one in the charts. Almost 80% of the initial Japanese shipment was sold within two days.<ref name="sales">{{cite web | author=Fahey, Rob | year=2006 | title=Shadow of the Colossus goes in at number one | url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/content_page.php?aid=12757 | work=[http://www.gamesindustry.biz/ Games Industry] | accessdate=July 21 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> These figures compare favorably with ''Ico'', which was well received by critics but failed to sell a significant number of copies.<ref name="sales2">{{cite web | author=kellercl | year=2006 | title=PS2 Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://sony.controllerfreaks.com/review.asp?RevID=375 | work=[http://controllerfreaks.com/ ControllerFreaks] | accessdate=July 24 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> The game was placed on Sony's list of [[List of Sony Greatest Hits games|Greatest Hits]] titles on August 8, 2006.<ref name="greatesthits">{{cite web | author=Surette, Tim | year=2006 | title=Five added to PS2 Greatest Hits | url=http://www.gamespot.com/ps2/adventure/wandaandthecolossus/news.html?sid=6155274 | work=[http://www.gamespot.com/ GameSpot] | accessdate=August 4 | accessyear=2006}}</ref><ref name="greatesthits2">{{cite web | editor=Sony Computer Entertainment staff | year=2006 | title=PlayStation 2 – Greatest Hits | url=http://www.us.playstation.com/PS2/GreatestHits | work=[http://www.us.playstation.com/ PlayStation.com] | accessdate=August 4 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

Unlike ''Ico'', ''Shadow'' received far more exposure, due in part to Sony putting its weight behind a massive advertising campaign.<ref name="kikizo">{{cite web | author=Kikizo site staff | year=2006 | title=Colossus Slays EA, Drags Ico Along | url=http://games.kikizo.com/news/200602/118.asp | work=[http://www.kikizo.com/ Kikizo] | accessdate=July 26 | accessyear=2006}}</ref> It was advertised in game magazines, on [[television advertisement|television]] and on the [[Internet marketing|internet]], including a [[viral marketing]] campaign that was launched by a website called "[http://giantology.typepad.com/ Giantology]" in October 2005. The site posted links to several websites claiming that the remains of five giants resembling certain colossi had been discovered in various parts of the world. The website has since been taken down. Some speculate that ''Ico''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s sales figures could have been improved if similar advertising efforts were made before its release.<ref name="eurogamer2">{{cite web | author=Reed, Kirstan | year=2005 | title=First Impressions – Shadow of the Colossus | url=http://www.eurogamer.net/article.php?article_id=59445 | work=[http://www.eurogamer.net/ Euro Gamer] | accessdate=July 26 | accessyear=2006}}</ref>

===Critical response===
